<h1><a href="../">Perl Advent Calendar 2010-12</a>-15</h1>
<h2 align="center">$HOME for the holidays</h2>
<h3 align="center">by Jerrad Pierce</h3>
<p>You're probably aware that saintly coders don't use tained data, but were you aware that you should also clean your environment? <tt><a href="http://search.cpan.org/perldoc?Env::Sanctify" title="Env::Sanctify">Env::Sanctify</a></tt> simplifies the process of cleaning <span style="font-style: italic">%ENV</span> with regular expressions, and restoring it later. If you're only mildly concerned with security, or unsure where to begin, <tt><a href="http://search.cpan.org/perldoc?Env::Sanctify::Auto" title="Env::Sanctify::Auto">Env::Sanctify::Auto</a></tt> will delint your environment automatically.</p>
<pre><span class="c">% perl -MEnv::Sanctify::Auto -e 'my $env = Env::Sanctify::Auto->new(); print `env`'
&hellip;
VISUAL=emacs
HOME=/home/kringle
GROUP=kringle
SHELL=/bin/tcsh
PATH=/usr/bin:/usr/bin/local
% env
&hellip;
VISUAL=emacs
HOME=/home/kringle
GROUP=kringle
SHELL=/bin/tcsh
PATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin:/usr/bin/X11:/usr/games</span></pre>
